[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-tech-stack.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [tech-stack, next.js, typescript, postgresql, react]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-001: Technology Stack
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Use **Next.js 16** (App Router, webpack bundler) with **TypeScript 5**, **PostgreSQL**, and **React 19**.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **Next.js App Router**: Unified server/client rendering, built-in API routes eliminates separate backend service
[CLAUDE] - **TypeScript**: Type safety across API contracts, service layer, and UI components
[CLAUDE] - **PostgreSQL**: Relational integrity for multi-tenant data; organization/project/bug hierarchy maps naturally to relational model
[CLAUDE] - **React 19 + shadcn/ui**: Modern component primitives with Tailwind CSS 4
[CLAUDE] - **Zod 4**: Runtime schema validation at API boundaries (all request body parsing uses Zod-compatible manual checks)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Webpack bundler (not Turbopack) chosen for stability — noted in `npm run dev` (`--webpack` flag)
[CLAUDE] - PostgreSQL worker thread architecture needed due to Next.js process model (see [Database Architecture](../systems/bug_tracker/database/schema.md))
[CLAUDE] - In-memory SQLite test backend added to keep unit tests fast without Docker
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Alternatives Considered
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Separate Express API backend — rejected to keep deployment simple
[CLAUDE] - Turbopack — not yet adopted, webpack used explicitly
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-database-worker.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [database, worker-thread, postgresql, architecture]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-002: PostgreSQL Worker Thread Architecture
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] PostgreSQL connections are managed in a **dedicated Worker thread** (`postgres-worker.ts`), pre-built to `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Next.js App Router runs route handlers in a serverless/edge-like execution model where persistent connection pools can cause issues (connection leaks, cold start overhead, module reuse across requests).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Isolating PostgreSQL in a Worker thread:
[CLAUDE] - Keeps the connection pool alive across requests without polluting the main thread
[CLAUDE] - Avoids the "pg client shared across hot-reloaded modules" problem in `next dev`
[CLAUDE] - Allows the worker to be independently bundled by esbuild
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Worker must be built before `next dev` starts — handled by `predev` npm script
[CLAUDE] - Worker is also built as part of `npm run build`
[CLAUDE] - Tests use an in-memory backend to avoid this complexity entirely
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Build Commands
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # Build worker only
[CLAUDE] npm run build:db-worker
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Runs automatically before dev
[CLAUDE] npm run dev  # predev hook builds worker first
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-dual-auth.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 4
[CLAUDE] tags: [auth, session, api-key, extension, agent]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-003: Dual Authentication Strategy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The platform uses two distinct authentication mechanisms:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. **Session cookies** — for human users via the web app
[CLAUDE] 2. **Bearer tokens / API keys** — for the Chrome extension and agent API
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Session cookies with `HttpOnly` are appropriate for browser-based flows and provide CSRF protection
[CLAUDE] - The Chrome extension cannot reliably share session cookies across origins, so it uses a Bearer token returned at login
[CLAUDE] - The agent API (`/api/agent/*`) is machine-to-machine — it uses a static API key to avoid requiring browser session infrastructure
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Implementation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - `getAuthenticatedSessionFromRequest()` — reads cookie
[CLAUDE] - `getAuthenticatedSessionFromExtensionRequest()` — reads `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header
[CLAUDE] - `requireAgentApiUser()` — validates API key from request
[CLAUDE] - `requireAdminUser()` — validates admin role from either session type
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Three separate auth code paths must be maintained
[CLAUDE] - Extension login creates a token stored like a session but returned in the response body (not as a cookie)
[CLAUDE] - Agent API keys are managed separately from user sessions
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
